"SECTION3_PARAGRAPH1" = "While a hearing aid does not restore hearing, it can help you hear sounds that you want to hear better. Advancements have made hearing aids more common, customizable, and useful in day-to-day life. Hearing aids can also be tuned for each ear in case you have more hearing loss in one ear than the other.";
"SECTION4_PARAGRAPH2" = "Talk to your doctor if:";
"SECTION1_PARAGRAPH1" = "Hearing loss is common and impacts people of all ages. For most people, their ability to hear will naturally change over time. It’s typical that as people get older, it gets harder for them to hear sounds such as a conversation in a loud restaurant. This is a natural progression that can start early in life. As people age, the hair cells in the inner ear become more brittle, get shorter, and become less effective at sensing sound.";
"SECTION3_PARAGRAPH3" = "You might notice the most difference in noisy environments, such as a birthday party. The hearing aids can help you pick up conversation that may have been drowned out before. You might also notice more quiet sounds coming through when you’re watching TV.";
"SECTION2_PARAGRAPH2" = "The test typically consists of a series of tones at different frequencies and volumes. You signal which ones you can hear and the results create an audiogram, which is a chart of your hearing. The louder a frequency needs to be for you to hear it, the greater your hearing loss.";
"SECTION2_PARAGRAPH4" = "There are two main ways to get a hearing aid. Over-the-counter hearing aids are designed for mild to moderate hearing loss and don’t require a prescription from a doctor. You can often set them up yourself and adjust them to your preference. Certain AirPods Pro can work as a hearing aid for this level of hearing loss once you’ve taken a hearing test. If you have severe or profound hearing loss, you’ll need a hearing aid that’s tuned for you by a doctor.";
"SECTION1_PARAGRAPH3" = "Losing your hearing can affect your ability to communicate with those around you. If you can’t hear someone fully, you’re missing things that make it easier to connect and participate in conversation. You might also notice it’s hard to hear in noisy places or needing to turn up the TV volume. Mild to moderate hearing loss can create a sense of isolation and contribute to mental health concerns such as depression. Untreated hearing loss has also been linked to cognitive decline and falls.";
